1427","1385–1410":"1385–1410","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","Abt 1400":"circa 1400","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","Abt 1360":"circa 1360","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1427":"1427","Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England":"Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England","Yardley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Yardley, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1365–1415":"1365–1415","1362–Male":"1362–Deceased","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1380–1427":"1380–1427","1385–1410":"1385–1410","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","Abt 1400":"about 1400","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","Abt 1360":"about 1360","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1427":"1427","Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England":"Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England","Yardley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lovell  , derived from Anglo-Norman French<i>lou</i> ‘wolf’ + the diminutive suffix <i>-el</i>.","History: Lowell is the surname of one of America's most distinguished NewEngland families, which have been prominent for over 200 years. Itsfounder, John Lowell (1743–1802), was a legislator and judge. Thecity of Lowell, MA was named in honor of his son Francis Cabot Lowell(1775–1817), a textile manufacturer."],"variants":[{"name":"Lovell","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lovel</i> ‘wolf cub’, a diminutive of <i>lou</i>, <i>love</i> ‘wolf’. Compare   Love   and   Low  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Lowell was born in 1365, in Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England, her father, James Lowell, was 20 and her mother, Mary Baskerville, was 20. She married Sir Hugh Berwick in 1384, in Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1415, in Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1365–1415":"1365–1415","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1380–1427":"1380–1427","1385–1410":"1385–1410","1345–1400":"1345–1400","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1427":"1427","Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England":"Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Beachampton, Buckinghamshire, England","Yardley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Yardley, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1365–1415":"1365–1415","1362–Ma